# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fmod-audio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] The first example of adaptive music is generally said to have been in *Space Invaders* by Taito in 1978.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] The game's simple background music, a four-note ostinato which repeats continuously throughout gameplay, increases in tempo as time goes on and the aliens descend upon the player.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] However, this music could also be considered sound effects for the aliens' movement, so some argue this is not an example of adaptive music.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] George Lucas' video game development group LucasArts (before becoming Lucasfilm Games) created and patented the iMUSE interactive music system in the early 1990s, which was used to synchronise video game music with game events.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] The first game to make use of this system was *Monkey Island 2: LeChuck's Revenge* in 1991.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Vertical orchestration is the technique in which the music's arrangement is changed.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Musical layers are added and removed in response to game events to affect the music's texture, intensity, and emotional feel without interrupting the flow of music.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Layers are generally faded in and out for smoother transitions.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] In video games, this technique may be used for more subtle game events than horizontal re-sequencing, such as an increase or decrease in intensity during a battle.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] In *Dead Space 2*, the background music appears to be arranged into four layers, each a stereo track corresponding with a specific level of "fear".
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Each of these layers is then either individually or collectively mixed during gameplay depending on a variety of game variables, such as the distance the player is from enemies.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Horizontal re-sequencing is the technique in which different pieces of music are transitioned between.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Musical pieces in a “branching” sequence are transitioned between in response to game events.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] The most simple kind of transition is a crossfade; when triggered by an event, the old piece is faded out while the new piece fades in.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Another kind is phrase branching; in this case, the change to the next segment starts when the current musical phrase has ended.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Another kind involves using dedicated "bridge" transitions, which are sections of music composed to join the two pieces of music together.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] In video games, this technique may be used for more significant game events, such as a change in location, beginning of a battle, or opening of a menu, as it generally draws more attention and makes a greater impact than vertical orchestration.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Some video games generate musical content live using algorithms instead of relying solely on pre-made musical pieces (such as in horizontal re-sequencing and vertical orchestration).
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] Some video games, such as *Rez* and *Extase*, synchronise their sound effects with the background music to blend them together.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] This is done by delaying playback of the sound effects after they're triggered by the player.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] The music game *Sound Shapes* uses an adaptive soundtrack to reward the player.
[src:fmod-audio/adaptive-music] As the player improves at the game and collects more "coins", the soundtrack, which is entirely composed of the melodies and beats created by these "coins", intensifies.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] In a digital audio system, an analog electrical signal representing the sound is converted with an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) into a digital signal, typically using pulse-code modulation (PCM).
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] This digital signal can then be recorded, edited, modified, and copied using computers, audio playback machines, and other digital tools.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] For playback, a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) performs the reverse process, converting a digital signal back into an analog signal, which is then sent through an audio power amplifier and ultimately to a loudspeaker.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio systems may include compression, storage, processing, and transmission components.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Conversion to a digital format allows convenient manipulation, storage, transmission, and retrieval of an audio signal.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Unlike analog audio, in which making copies of a recording results in generation loss and degradation of signal quality, digital audio allows an infinite number of copies to be made without any degradation of signal quality.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio technologies are used in the recording, manipulation, mass-production, and distribution of sound, including recordings of songs, instrumental pieces, podcasts, sound effects, and other sounds.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Modern online music distribution depends on digital recording and data compression.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The availability of music as data files, rather than as physical objects, has significantly reduced the costs of distribution as well as making it easier to share copies.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Before digital audio, the music industry distributed and sold music by selling physical copies in the form of records and cassette tapes.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] With digital audio and online distribution systems such as iTunes, companies sell digital sound files to consumers, which the consumer receives over the Internet.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Popular streaming services such as Apple Music, Spotify, or YouTube, offer temporary access to the digital file, and are now the most common form of music consumption.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] An analog audio system converts physical waveforms of sound into electrical representations of those waveforms by use of a transducer, such as a microphone.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The sounds are then stored on an analog medium such as magnetic tape, or transmitted through an analog medium such as a telephone line or radio.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The process is reversed for reproduction: the electrical audio signal is amplified and then converted back into physical waveforms via a loudspeaker.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Analog audio retains its fundamental wave-like characteristics throughout its storage, transformation, duplication, and amplification.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Analog audio signals are susceptible to noise and distortion, due to the innate characteristics of electronic circuits and associated devices.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Disturbances in a digital system do not result in error unless they are so large as to result in a symbol being misinterpreted as another symbol or disturbing the sequence of symbols.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] It is, therefore, generally possible to have an entirely error-free digital audio system in which no noise or distortion is introduced between conversion to digital format and conversion back to analog.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] A digital audio signal may be encoded for correction of any errors that might occur in the storage or transmission of the signal.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] This technique, known as channel coding, is essential for broadcast or recorded digital systems to maintain bit accuracy.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Eight-to-fourteen modulation is the channel code used for the audio compact disc (CD).
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] If an audio signal is analog, a digital audio system starts with an ADC that converts an analog signal to a digital signal.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The ADC runs at a specified sampling rate and converts at a known bit resolution.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] CD audio, for example, has a sampling rate of 44.1 kHz (44,100 samples per second), and has 16-bit resolution for each stereo channel.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Analog signals that have not already been bandlimited must be passed through an anti-aliasing filter before conversion, to prevent the aliasing distortion that is caused by audio signals with frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency (half the sampling rate).
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] A digital audio signal may be stored or transmitted.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio can be stored on a CD, a digital audio player, a hard drive, a USB flash drive, or any other digital data storage device.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The digital signal may be altered through digital signal processing, where it may be filtered or have effects applied.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Sample-rate conversion, including upsampling and downsampling, may be used to change signals that have been encoded with a different sampling rate to a common sampling rate prior to processing.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Audio data compression techniques, such as MP3, Advanced Audio Coding (AAC), Opus, Ogg Vorbis, or FLAC, are commonly employed to reduce the file size.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio can be carried over digital audio interfaces such as AES3 or MADI.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio can be carried over a network using audio over Ethernet, audio over IP or other streaming media standards and systems.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] For playback, digital audio must be converted back to an analog signal with a DAC.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] According to the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, with some practical and theoretical restrictions, a band-limited version of the original analog signal can be accurately reconstructed from the digital signal.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] During conversion, audio data can be embedded with a digital watermark to prevent piracy and unauthorized use.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Watermarking is done using a direct-sequence spread-spectrum (DSSS) method.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The audio information is then modulated by a pseudo-noise (PN) sequence, then shaped within the frequency domain and put back in the original signal.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The strength of the embedding determines the strength of the watermark on the audio data.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Pulse-code modulation (PCM) was invented by British scientist Alec Reeves in 1937.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Chapin Cutler of Bell Labs filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM), a data compression algorithm.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Schroeder at Bell Labs developed a form of LPC called adaptive predictive coding (APC), a perceptual coding algorithm that exploited the masking properties of the human ear, followed in the early 1980s with the code-excited linear prediction (CELP) algorithm.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding, a lossy compression method first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which was developed by J.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The MDCT is the basis for most audio coding standards, such as Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3 (MPEG Layer III), AAC, Windows Media Audio (WMA), Opus and Vorbis (Ogg).
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] PCM was used in telecommunications applications long before its first use in commercial broadcast and recording.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Commercial digital recording was pioneered in Japan by NHK and Nippon Columbia and their Denon brand, in the 1960s.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The first commercial digital recordings were released in 1971.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The BBC also began to experiment with digital audio in the 1960s.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] By the early 1970s, it had developed a 2-channel recorder, and in 1972 it deployed a digital audio transmission system that linked its broadcast center to its remote transmitters.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The first 16-bit PCM recording in the United States was made by Thomas Stockham at the Santa Fe Opera in 1976, on a Soundstream recorder.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] An improved version of the Soundstream system was used to produce several classical recordings by Telarc in 1978.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The 3M digital multitrack recorder in development at the time was based on BBC technology.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The first all-digital album recorded on this machine was Ry Cooder's *Bop till You Drop* in 1979.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] British record label Decca began development of its own 2-track digital audio recorders in 1978 and released the first European digital recording in 1979.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Popular professional digital multitrack recorders produced by Sony/Studer (DASH) and Mitsubishi (ProDigi) in the early 1980s helped to bring about digital recording's acceptance by the major record companies.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Machines for these formats had their own transports built in as well, using reel-to-reel tape in either 1/4, 1/2, or 1-inch widths, with the audio data being recorded to the tape using a multi-track stationary tape head.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] PCM adaptors allowed for stereo digital audio recording on a conventional NTSC or PAL video tape recorder.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The 1982 introduction of the CD by Philips and Sony popularized digital audio with consumers.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] ADAT became available in the early 1990s, which allowed eight-track 44.1 or 48 kHz recording on S-VHS cassettes, and DTRS performed a similar function with Hi8 tapes.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Like the DAT cassette, ProDigi and DASH machines also accommodated the obligatory 44.1 kHz sampling rate, but also 48 kHz on all machines, and eventually a 96 kHz sampling rate.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Unlike analog systems, modern digital audio workstations and audio interfaces allow as many channels in as many different sampling rates as the computer can effectively run at a single time.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Avid Audio and Steinberg released the first digital audio workstation software programs in 1989.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio workstations make multitrack recording and mixing much easier for large projects, which would otherwise be difficult with analog equipment.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The rapid development and wide adoption of PCM digital telephony was enabled by metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) switched capacitor (SC) circuit technology, developed in the early 1970s.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] This led to the development of PCM codec-filter chips in the late 1970s.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] The silicon-gate CMOS (complementary MOS) PCM codec-filter chip, developed by David A.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Black in 1980, has since been the industry standard for digital telephony.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio is used in broadcasting of audio.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Standard technologies include Digital audio broadcasting (DAB), Digital Radio Mondiale (DRM), HD Radio and In-band on-channel (IBOC).
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio in recording applications is stored on audio-specific technologies including CD, DAT, Digital Compact Cassette (DCC) and MiniDisc.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio may be stored in a standard audio file formats and stored on a Hard disk recorder, Blu-ray or DVD-Audio.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Files may be played back on smartphones, computers or MP3 player.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Digital audio resolution is measured in audio bit depth.
[src:fmod-audio/digital-audio] Most digital audio formats use either 16-bit, 24-bit, and 32-bit resolution.
[src:fmod-audio/fmod] The FMOD sound system is supplied as a programmer's API and authoring tool, similar to a digital audio workstation.
[src:fmod-audio/fmod] The FMOD sound system has an advanced plugin architecture that can be used to extend the support of audio formats or to develop new output types, e.g. for streaming.
[src:fmod-audio/fmod] FMOD contains support for AMD TrueAudio, and Sound Blaster hardware acceleration.
[src:fmod-audio/fmod] FMOD has been used in many high-profile commercial games since release; this is a partial list.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Pan pots split audio signals into left and right channels via an internal architecture that determines how much of the source signal is sent to the left and right buses.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] This signal distribution is often called a taper or pan law.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] When centered (at 12 o'clock), the signal is sent equally to each bus.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] If the two output buses are later recombined into a monaural signal, then a pan law of −6 dB is desirable.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] If the two output buses are to remain stereo then a law of −3 dB is desirable.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] A law of −4.5 dB at center is a compromise between the two.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] A pan control fully rotated to one side results in the source being sent at full strength (0 dB) to one bus (either the left or right channel) and zero strength (−∞ dB) to the other.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Regardless of the pan setting, the overall sound power level remains approximately constant.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Because of the phantom center phenomenon, sound panned to the center position is perceived as coming from *between* the left and right speakers.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Panning in audio borrows its name from panning action in moving image technology; the term *panning* is derived from *panorama*.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Simple analog pan controls only change relative level; they don't add reverb to replace direct signal, phase changes, modify the spectrum, or change delay timing.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Panning can also be used in an audio mixer to reduce or reverse the stereo width of a stereo signal.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] For instance, the left and right channels of a stereo source can be panned straight up, which is sent equally to both the left output and the right output of the mixer, creating a dual mono signal.
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] An early panning process was used in the development of Fantasound, an early pioneering stereophonic sound reproduction system for *Fantasia* (1940).
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Before pan pots were available, "a three-way switch was used to assign the track to the left output, right output, or both (the center)".
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] Ubiquitous in the Billboard charts throughout the middle and late 1960s, clear examples include the Beatles's "Strawberry Fields Forever" and Jimi Hendrix's "Purple Haze", Stevie Wonder's "Living for the City".
[src:fmod-audio/panning-audio] In the Beatles's "A Day In The Life" Lennon's vocals are switched to the extreme right on the first two strophes, on the third strophe they are switched center then extreme left, and switched left on the final strophe while during the bridge McCartney's vocals are switched extreme right.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] In acoustics, **reverberation** (commonly shortened to **reverb**) is a persistence of sound after it is produced.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] It is often created when a sound is reflected on surfaces, causing multiple reflections that build up and then decay as the sound is absorbed by the surfaces of objects in the space – which could include furniture, people, and air.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] This is most noticeable when the sound source stops but the reflections continue, their amplitude decreasing, until zero is reached.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation is frequency dependent: the length of the decay, or reverberation time, receives special consideration in the architectural design of spaces which need to have specific reverberation times to achieve optimum performance for their intended activity.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] In comparison to a distinct echo, that is detectable at a minimum of 50 to 100 ms after the previous sound, reverberation is the occurrence of reflections that arrive in a sequence of less than approximately 50 ms.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] As time passes, the amplitude of the reflections gradually reduces to non-noticeable levels.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation is not limited to indoor spaces as it exists in forests and other outdoor environments where reflection exists.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation occurs naturally when a person sings, talks, or plays an instrument acoustically in a hall or performance space with sound-reflective surfaces.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation is applied artificially by using reverb effects, which simulate reverb through means including echo chambers, vibrations sent through metal, and digital processing.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Although reverberation can add naturalness to recorded sound by adding a sense of space, it can also reduce speech intelligibility, especially when noise is also present.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] People with hearing loss, including users of hearing aids, frequently report difficulty in understanding speech in reverberant, noisy situations.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation is also a significant source of mistakes in automatic speech recognition.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] When it comes to accurately measuring reverberation time with a meter, the term *T60* (an abbreviation for reverberation time 60 dB) is used.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] T60 provides an objective reverberation time measurement.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] It is defined as the time it takes for the sound pressure level to reduce by 60 dB, measured after the generated test signal is abruptly ended.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation time is frequently stated as a single value if measured as a wideband signal (20 Hz to 20 kHz).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] However, being frequency-dependent, it can be more precisely described in terms of frequency bands (one octave, 1/3 octave, 1/6 octave, etc.).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Being frequency dependent, the reverberation time measured in narrow bands will differ depending on the frequency band being measured.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] For precision, it is important to know what ranges of frequencies are being described by a reverberation time measurement.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] In the late 19th century, Wallace Clement Sabine started experiments at Harvard University to investigate the impact of absorption on the reverberation time.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Using a portable wind chest and organ pipes as a sound source, a stopwatch and his ears, he measured the time from interruption of the source to inaudibility (a difference of roughly 60 dB).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] He found that the reverberation time is proportional to room dimensions and inversely proportional to the amount of absorption present.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The optimum reverberation time for a space in which music is played depends on the type of music that is to be played in the space.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Rooms used for speech typically need a shorter reverberation time so that speech can be understood more clearly.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] If the reflected sound from one syllable is still heard when the next syllable is spoken, it may be difficult to understand what was said.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] "Cat", "cab", and "cap" may all sound very similar.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] If on the other hand the reverberation time is too short, tonal balance and loudness may suffer.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation effects are often used in studios to add depth to sounds.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation changes the perceived spectral structure of a sound but does not alter the pitch.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Basic factors that affect a room's reverberation time include the size and shape of the enclosure as well as the materials used in the construction of the room.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Every object placed within the enclosure can also affect this reverberation time, including people and their belongings.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Historically, reverberation time could only be measured using a level recorder (a plotting device which graphs the noise level against time on a ribbon of moving paper).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] A loud noise is produced, and as the sound dies away the trace on the level recorder will show a distinct slope.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Analysis of this slope reveals the measured reverberation time.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Some modern digital sound level meters can carry out this analysis automatically.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Several methods exist for measuring reverberation time.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] An impulse can be measured by creating a sufficiently loud noise (which must have a defined cut-off point).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Impulse noise sources such as a blank pistol shot or balloon burst may be used to measure the impulse response of a room.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Alternatively, a random noise signal such as pink noise or white noise may be generated through a loudspeaker, and then turned off.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] This is known as the interrupted method, and the measured result is known as the interrupted response.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] A two-port measurement system can also be used to measure noise introduced into a space and compare it to what is subsequently measured in the space.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Consider sound reproduced by a loudspeaker into a room.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] A recording of the sound in the room can be made and compared to what was sent to the loudspeaker.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The two signals can be compared mathematically.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] This two port measurement system uses a Fourier transform to mathematically derive the impulse response of the room.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] From the impulse response, the reverberation time can be calculated.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Using a two-port system allows reverberation time to be measured with signals other than loud impulses.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Music or recordings of other sounds can be used.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] This allows measurements to be taken in a room after the audience is present.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Reverberation time is usually stated as a decay time and is measured in seconds.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] There may or may not be any statement of the frequency band used in the measurement.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Decay time is the time it takes the signal to diminish 60 dB below the original sound.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] It is often difficult to inject enough sound into the room to measure a decay of 60 dB, particularly at lower frequencies.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] If the decay is linear, it is sufficient to measure a drop of 20 dB and multiply the time by 3, or a drop of 30 dB and multiply the time by 2.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] These are the so-called T20 and T30 measurement methods.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The RT60 reverberation time measurement is defined in the ISO 3382-1 standard for performance spaces, the ISO 3382-2 standard for ordinary rooms, and the ISO 3382-3 for open-plan offices, as well as the ASTM E2235 standard.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The concept of reverberation time implicitly supposes that the decay rate of the sound is exponential, so that the sound level diminishes regularly, at a rate of so many dB per second.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] It is not often the case in real rooms, depending on the disposition of reflective, dispersive and absorbing surfaces.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Moreover, successive measurement of the sound level often yields very different results, as differences in phase in the exciting sound build up in notably different sound waves.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Schroeder published "A new method of Measuring Reverberation Time" in the *Journal of the Acoustical Society of America*.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] He proposed to measure, not the power of the sound, but the energy, by integrating it.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] This made it possible to show the variation in the rate of decay and to free acousticians from the necessity of averaging many measurements.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Sabine's reverberation equation was developed in the late 1890s in an empirical fashion.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] He established a relationship between the *T*60 of a room, its volume, and its total absorption (in sabins).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] where *c*20 is the speed of sound in the room (at 20 °C), *V* is the volume of the room in m3, *S* total surface area of room in m2, *a* is the average absorption coefficient of room surfaces, and the product *Sa* is the total absorption in sabins.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The total absorption in sabins (and hence reverberation time) generally changes depending on frequency (which is defined by the acoustic properties of the space).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The equation does not take into account room shape or losses from the sound traveling through the air (important in larger spaces).
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Most rooms absorb less sound energy in the lower frequency ranges resulting in longer reverb times at lower frequencies.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Sabine concluded that the reverberation time depends upon the reflectivity of sound from various surfaces available inside the hall.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] If the reflection is coherent, the reverberation time of the hall will be longer; the sound will take more time to die out.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] where critical distance $d_{c}$ is measured in meters, volume V is measured in m³, and reverberation time *RT*60 is measured in seconds.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Eyring's reverberation time equation was proposed by Carl F.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] This equation aims to better estimate the reverberation time in small rooms with relatively large quantities of sound absorption, identified by Eyring as "dead" rooms.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] These rooms tend to have lower reverberation times than larger, more acoustically live rooms.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Eyring's equation is similar in form to Sabine's equation, but includes modifications to logarithmically scale the absorption term.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The units and variables within the equation are the same as those defined for Sabine's equation.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Eyring's equation was developed from first principles using an image source model of sound reflection, as opposed to Sabine's empirical approach.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The experimental results obtained by Sabine generally agree with Eyring's equation since the two formulae become identical for very live rooms, the type in which Sabine worked.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] However, Eyring's equation becomes more valid for smaller rooms with large quantities of absorption.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] As a result, the Eyring equation is often implemented to estimate the reverberation time in recording studio control rooms or other critical listening environments with high quantities of sound absorption.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The Sabine equation tends to over-predict reverberation time for small rooms with high amounts of absorption.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] For this reason, reverberation time calculators available for smaller recording studio environments, such as home recording studios, often use Eyring's equation.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The absorption coefficient of a material is a number between 0 and 1 which indicates the proportion of sound which is absorbed by the surface compared to the proportion which is reflected back to the room.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] A large, fully open window would offer no reflection as any sound reaching it would pass straight out and no sound would be reflected.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] This would have an absorption coefficient of 1.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Conversely, a thick, smooth painted concrete ceiling would be the acoustic equivalent of a mirror and have an absorption coefficient very close to 0.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Absorption coefficients are frequency-dependent and are typically reported at the standard octave band centre frequencies of 125, 250, 500, 1000, 2000, and 4000 Hz.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] A single-number rating called the weighted sound absorption coefficient (*α*w) can be derived from the frequency-dependent values according to ISO 11654.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] The standard laboratory method for measuring absorption coefficients is ISO 354, which uses a reverberation room and determines the random-incidence absorption coefficient from the change in reverberation time after placing a test specimen in the room.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] An alternative method using an impedance tube (ISO 10534-2) measures the normal-incidence absorption coefficient for small material samples.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Values measured in a reverberation room can exceed 1.0 because edge diffraction effects increase the effective absorbing area beyond the physical dimensions of the specimen.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Gregorian chant may have developed in response to the long reverberation time of cathedrals, limiting the number of notes that could be sung before blending chaotically.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] Artificial reverberation is applied to sound using reverb effects.
[src:fmod-audio/reverberation] These simulate reverb through means including echo chambers, vibrations sent through metal, and digital processing.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] A **sound effect** (or **audio effect**) is an artificially created or enhanced sound, or sound process used to emphasize artistic or other content of films, television shows, live performance, animation, video games, music, or other media.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In motion picture and television production, a sound effect is a sound recorded and presented to make a specific storytelling or creative point *without* the use of dialogue or music.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Traditionally, in the twentieth century, they were created with Foley.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The term often refers to a process applied to a recording, without necessarily referring to the recording itself.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In professional motion picture and television production, dialogue, music, and sound effects recordings are treated as separate elements.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Dialogue and music recordings are never referred to as sound effects, even though the processes applied to such as reverberation or flanging effects, often are called *sound effects*.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] This area and sound design have been slowly merged since the late-twentieth century.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The term *sound effect* dates back to the early days of radio.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In its *Year Book 1931* the BBC published a major article about "The Use of Sound Effects".
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] It considers sound effects deeply linked with broadcasting and states: "It would be a great mistake to think of them as analogous to punctuation marks and accents in print.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] They should never be *inserted* into a program already existing.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] According to the author, "It is axiomatic that every Sound Effect, to whatever category it belongs, *must* register in the listener's mind instantaneously.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Each of these sound effect categories is specialized, with sound editors known as specialists in an area of sound effects (e.g. a *Car cutter* or *Guns cutter*).
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Foley is another method of adding sound effects.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Foley is more of a technique for creating sound effects than a type of sound effect, but it is often used for creating the incidental real-world sounds that are very specific to what is going on onscreen, such as footsteps.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] With this technique, the action onscreen is essentially recreated to try to match it as closely as possible.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If done correctly it is very hard for audiences to tell what sounds were added and what sounds were originally recorded (location sound).
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In the early days of film and radio, Foley artists would add sounds in real time or pre-recorded sound effects would be played back from analog discs in real time (while watching the picture).
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Today, with effects held in digital format, it is easy to create any required sequence to be played in any desired timeline.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In the days of silent film, sound effects were added by the operator of a theater organ or photoplayer, both of which also supplied the soundtrack of the film.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Theater organ sound effects are usually electric or electro-pneumatic, and activated by a button pressed with the hand or foot.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Photoplayer operators activate sound effects either by flipping switches on the machine or pulling *cow-tail* pull-strings, which hang above.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Sounds like bells and drums are made mechanically, sirens and horns electronically.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Due to its smaller size, a photoplayer usually has fewer special effects than a theater organ or less complex ones.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The principles involved with modern video game sound effects (since the introduction of sample playback) are essentially the same as those of motion pictures.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Typically a game project requires two jobs to be completed: sounds must be recorded or selected from a library and a sound engine must be programmed so that those sounds can be incorporated into the game's interactive environment.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In earlier computers and video game systems, sound effects were typically produced using sound synthesis.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In modern systems, the increases in storage capacity and playback quality has allowed sampled sound to be used.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The modern systems also frequently utilize positional audio, often with hardware acceleration, and real-time audio post-processing, which can also be tied to the 3D graphics development.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Based on the internal state of the game, multiple different calculations can be made.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] This will allow for, for example, realistic sound dampening, echoes and Doppler effect.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Historically the simplicity of game environments reduced the required number of sounds needed, and thus only one or two people were directly responsible for the sound recording and design.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] As the video game business has grown and computer sound reproduction quality has increased, however, the team of sound designers dedicated to game projects has likewise grown and the demands placed on them may now approach those of mid-budget motion pictures.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Some pieces of music use sound effects that are made by a musical instrument or by other means.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] An early example is the 18th century Toy Symphony.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Richard Wagner in the opera *Das Rheingold* (1869) lets a choir of anvils introduce the scene of the dwarfs who have to work in the mines, similar to the introduction of the dwarfs in the 1937 Disney movie *Snow White*.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Klaus Doldingers soundtrack for the 1981 movie *Das Boot* includes a title score with a sonar sound to reflect the U-boat setting.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] John Barry integrated into the title song of *Moonraker* (1979) a sound representing the beep of a Sputnik like satellite.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Gao, Jianliang, Zhao, Yuezhe, and Pan, Lili explained how sound absorption in the stage area influences the acoustics within an opera house auditorium.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Their research, using computer models and scale experiments, revealed that sound absorption significantly affects sound clarity and the time it takes for sound to fade, but not the volume.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] More absorption led to clearer sounds but quicker fades, showing the intricate dance between stage and auditorium acoustics.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In his book "Sound: A Reader in Theatre Practice," Brown effectively connects the dots between theory and practice in the world of theater sound.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] He presents an engaging look into how sound design in theater has evolved, blending historical insights with current philosophical thoughts.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Brown argues that the immersive nature of theater sound goes beyond traditional analysis, providing fresh perspectives on how sound interacts with societal contexts.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Brown offers a fresh look at Ovadija's exploration of sound in theater, questioning the traditional focus on visuals over audio.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] He points out the significant, yet often overlooked, role of sound in shaping theater's impact and experience.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Brown pushes for a broader appreciation of sound's essence in theater, beyond just supporting visuals, to acknowledge its deep influence on storytelling and audience immersion.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Rost explores the criteria for 'good sound' in theater through handbooks and prioritization as guiding principles.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] These criteria not only dictate the creation and selection of sounds to complement the narrative and mood but also aim to maintain audience focus.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Rost's analysis reveals underlying hierarchies in sound selection and emphasizes the need for further research into the historical and practical aspects of theater sound.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The most realistic sound effects may originate from original sources; the closest sound to machine-gun fire could be an original recording of actual machine guns.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Despite this, real life and actual practice do not always coincide with theory.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] When recordings of real life do not sound realistic on playback, Foley and effects are used to create more convincing sounds.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] For example, the realistic sound of bacon frying can be the crumpling of cellophane, while rain may be recorded as salt falling on a piece of tin foil.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Less realistic sound effects are digitally synthesized or sampled and sequenced (the same recording played repeatedly using a sequencer).
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] When the producer or content creator demands high-fidelity sound effects, the sound editor usually must augment his available library with new sound effects recorded in the field.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] When the required sound effect is of a small subject, such as scissors cutting, cloth ripping, or footsteps, the sound effect is best recorded in a studio, under controlled conditions in a process known as Foley.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Many sound effects cannot be recorded in a studio, such as explosions, gunfire, and automobile or aircraft maneuvers.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] These effects must be recorded by a professional audio engineer.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If the recordist requires a volley of cannon fire, they may contact historical re-enactors or gun enthusiasts.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Depending on the effect, recordists may use several DAT, hard disk, or Nagra recorders and a large number of microphones.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] During a cannon- and musket-fire recording session for the 2003 film *The Alamo*, conducted by Jon Johnson and Charles Maynes, two to three DAT machines were used.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] One machine was stationed near the cannon itself, so it could record the actual firing.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Another was stationed several hundred yards away, below the trajectory of the ball, to record the sound of the cannonball passing by.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] When the crew recorded musket fire, a set of microphones were arrayed close to the target (in this case a swine carcass) to record the musket-ball impacts.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] A counter-example is the common technique for recording an automobile.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] For recording *onboard* car sounds (which include the car interiors), a three-microphone technique is common.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Two microphones record the engine directly: one is taped to the underside of the hood, near the engine block.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The second microphone is covered in a wind screen and tightly attached to the rear bumper, within an inch or so of the tailpipe.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The third microphone, which is often a stereo microphone, is stationed inside the car to get the car interior.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Having all of these tracks at once gives a sound designer or audio engineer a great deal of control over how they want the car to sound.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In order to make the car more ominous or low, they can mix in more of the tailpipe recording; if they want the car to sound like it is running full throttle, they can mix in more of the engine recording and reduce the interior perspective.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In cartoons, a pencil being dragged down a washboard may be used to simulate the sound of a sputtering engine.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] What is considered today to be the first recorded sound effect was of Big Ben striking 10:30, 10:45, and 11:00.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] It was recorded on a brown wax cylinder by technicians at Edison House in London on July 16, 1890.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] This recording is currently in the public domain.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] As the car example demonstrates, the ability to make multiple simultaneous recordings of the same subject—through the use of several DAT or multitrack recorders—has made sound recording into a sophisticated craft.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The sound effect can be shaped by the sound editor or sound designer, not just for realism, but for emotional effect.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Once the sound effects are recorded or captured, they are usually loaded into a computer integrated with an audio non-linear editing system.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] This allows a sound editor or sound designer to heavily manipulate a sound to meet their needs.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The most common sound design tool is the use of layering to create a new, interesting sound out of two or three old, average sounds.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] For example, the sound of a bullet impact into a pig carcass may be mixed with the sound of a melon being gouged to add to the *stickiness* or *gore* of the effect.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If the effect is featured in a close-up, the designer may also add an *impact sweetener* from their library.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The sweetener may simply be the sound of a hammer pounding hardwood, equalized so that only the low-end can be heard.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The low end gives the three sounds together added weight so that the audience actually *feels* the weight of the bullet hit the victim.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If the victim is the villain, and his death is climactic, the sound designer may add reverb to the impact, in order to enhance the dramatic beat.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] And then, as the victim falls over in slow motion, the sound editor may add the sound of a broom whooshing by a microphone, pitch-shifted down and time-expanded to further emphasize the death.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If the film is science-fiction, the designer may phaser the *whoosh* to give it a more sci-fi feel.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] When creating sound effects for films, sound recordists and editors do not generally concern themselves with the verisimilitude or accuracy of the sounds they present.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] Sci-fi and fantasy genres can be more forgiving in terms of audience expectations; the listener will not be caught off guard as much by unusual sound effects.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In contrast, when creating sound effects for historical accuracy and realism, the listener likely had a lifetime of exposure to some of these sounds and so there are expectations of what they should sound like.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] In the previous example, the phased 'whoosh' of the victim's fall has no analog in real-life experience, but it is emotionally immediate.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If a sound editor uses such sounds in the context of emotional climax or a character's subjective experience, they can add to the drama of a situation in a way visuals simply cannot.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If a visual effects artist were to do something similar to the 'whooshing fall' example, it would probably look ridiculous or at least excessively melodramatic.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] The *conjectural sound* principle applies even to happenstance sounds, such as tires squealing, doorknobs turning or people walking.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If the sound editor wants to communicate that a driver is in a hurry to leave, they will cut the sound of tires squealing when the car accelerates from a stop; even if the car is on a dirt road, the effect will work if the audience is dramatically engaged.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] If a character is afraid of someone on the other side of a door, the turning of the doorknob can take a second or more, and the mechanism of the knob can possess dozens of clicking parts.
[src:fmod-audio/sound-effect] A skillful Foley artist can make someone walking calmly across the screen seem terrified simply by giving the actor a different gait.
